
text <12 Gates>
  text <The Prologue>
    block
      text <Childe of this discipline incline to me thine eare>
      text <And harkē to my doctrine with al thy diligēce>
      text <These words of wisedome in minde doe thou beare,>
      text <Which of olde fathers be true in sentence:>
      text <Liue cleane in soule, to God doe no offence.>
      text <Exalt thee not but rather keepe thee lowe,>
      text <Else will thy God in thee no wisdome sowe.>
    block
      text <From sinfull doctrine and wicked thought,>
      text <The holy spirite doth him withdraw,>
      text <Nilling to dwell where sinne is wrought:>
      text <Dread God therefore and obey his law:>
      text <A righteous man forsooke I neuer sawe:>
      text <Neyther his seede begge bread for neede:>
      text <In holy scripture this doe I reede.>
    block
      text <Make wisdome therefore thy mother to be,>
      text <And call on Prudence to be thy friend,>
      text <By pathes of truth they will guide thee,>
      text <With loue and honesty wheresoeuer thou wend:>
      text <Both vertuous to be, curteous and hend:>
      text <Pray God therefore that thou maist finde,>
      text <Wisedome and Prudence with mouth and minde.>
    block
      text <All manner good come with them shall,>
      text <And honestie by their hands innumerable,>
      text <Then into cumbrance shalt thou not fall,>
      text <So be they in riches incomparable:>
      text <To worship and profite they will thee able,>
      text <To cunning and all manner of grace,>
      text <Both here and after thy liues space.>
    block
      text <For these benefites which they doe bring,>
      text <I meane these vertues of prudence and sapience,>
      text <To whome I can compare nothing,>
      text <No riches, nor spices of redolence,>
      text <Aboue all treasure such is their excellence,>
      text <That whatsoeuer earthly precious is,>
      text <To them is compared as clay I wis.>
    block
      text <Infinite treasure to man they be,>
      text <Who vseth them shall friendship haue>
      text <With God in heauen and there him see,>
      text <After them therefore busily craue,>
      text <For bodie and soule they will both saue,>
      text <And here in goods thee multiply;>
      text <And afore princes thee dignifie.>
    block
      text <Thinke how Adam lost his wisedome,>
      text <Sampson his might which was so strong:>
      text <King Saule also lost his kingdome,>
      text <And Dauid was punished for his wrong:>
      text <In the Oke by the haire fayre Absolon hong,>
      text <King Ezechias by sicknes had punishment,>
      text <And many one moe for sinne was shent.>
    block
      text <But see how other which liued weele,>
      text <And to their God did no offence,>
      text <Such chastisement did neuer feele;>
      text <But God sheweth euer to them beneuolence,>
      text <Enoch and Hely were carried hence,>
      text <To Paradice, and orher good liuers were>
      text <Of God rewarded in diuerse mannere.>
    block
      text <Some had great Fortune, some great cunning,>
      text <Some had great peace, some great riches,>
      text <Some conquered lands to their great wynning▪>
      text <Some were exalted for their great meeknes,>
      text <Some other were saued from the cruelnes>
      text <Of Tyrants, Lyons, and of the hot furnace,>
      text <As Daniel and others in many a place.>
    block
      text <Thus to good liuers God sent great grace,>
      text <And vnto sinners great and sore punishment,>
      text <Some to amend in this life had space,>
      text <Some sodainely with fire from heauen were brent,>
      text <Sinfull Sodomites for euer were shent,>
      text <With Dathan and Abiron with many moe,>
      text <Which sunke for sinne to endles woe.>
    block
      text <Thus euer sith this world was wrought,>
      text <God hath rewarded both euill and good:>
      text <Thus if it may rest in thy thought,>
      text <From sinfull liuing to change thy moode.>
      text <If sinfull people this vnderstoode,>
      text <They ought to be afrayde God to offend,>
      text <And soone their sinfull liues to amend.>
    block
      text <Therefore with God looke thou beginne,>
      text <That he by grace may dwell with thee,>
      text <So shalt thou best to wisdome winne;>
      text <And knowledge of our great priuitie:>
      text <Nourish vertues, and from vices flee,>
      text <And trusting thou wilt thee well dispose,>
      text <Our secrets to thee I will disclose.>
    block
      text <Keepe thou them secreate and for me pray,>
      text <Looke that thou vse them to Gods pleasure,>
      text <Doo good with them what euer thou may;>
      text <For time thou shalt this life indure,>
      text <That after thy ende thou mayst be sure>
      text <In heauen for to rewarded be,>
      text <Which God graunt both to me and thee.>
    block
      text <FINIS>

  text <The Preface.>
    block
      text <O High incomprehensible and glorious Maiestie,>
      text <Whose luminous beames obtundeth our specula∣tion,>
      text <O trinehood in persons ô onehood in deity, t>
      text <Of Iherarchiall Iubilists gratulant glorification,>
      text <O piteous purifier of soules and pure perpetuation,>
      text <O deuiant from danger, ô drawer most debonayre,>
      text <From this troublesome vale of vanitie, ô our Exalter.>
    block
      text <O power, ô wisdome, ô goodnes inexplicable,>
      text <Supporte me, teach me, and be my gouernor,>
      text <That neuer my liuing to thee be displicable,>
      text <But that I acquite me to thee as true professor,>
      text <At this beginning good Lord heare my prayer,>
      text <Be nigh with grace for to inforce my will,>
      text <Graunt witt that I may mine intent fulfill.>
    block
      text <Most curious Cofer and copious of all treasure,>
      text <Thou art he from whome all goodnes doth discend,>
      text <To man and also to euery creature,>
      text <Thine handy-work therefore vouchsafe to defend,>
      text <That we no time in liuing here mispend,>
      text <With troth here graunt vs our liuing so to winne,>
      text <That into no danger of sinfulnes we rinne.>
    block
      text <And forasumch as we haue for thy sake>
      text <Renounced our wills, the world and fleshly lust,>
      text <As thine owne professors vs to thee take,>
      text <Sith in thee onely dependeth all our trust;>
      text <We can no further; to thee incline we must:>
      text <Thy secret treasure vouchsafe vnto vs,>
      text <Shew vs thy secrets and to vs be bounteous.>
    block
      text <And amongst others which be profest to thee,>
      text <I me present as one with humble submission,>
      text <Thy seruant beseeching that I may bee,>
      text <And true in liuing according to my profession,>
      text <In order Chanon Reguler of Bridlington;>
      text <Beseeching thee Lord thou wilt me spare,>
      text <To thy true seruants thy secrets to declare.>
    block
      text <In the beginning when thou mad'st all of nought,>
      text <A globous matter and darke vnder confusion,>
      text <By him the beginning marueilously was wrought,>
      text <Conteyning naturally all things without diuision:>
      text <Of which in six dayes he made cleere distinction:>
      text <As Genesis apertly doth record.>
      text <Then heauen and earth were perfected by his word.>
    block
      text <So through his will and power, out of one mas>
      text <Confused; was made each thing that being is,>
      text <But afore in glory as maker he was,>
      text <Now is and shall be without end I wis,>
      text <And purified soules vp to his blis>
      text <Shall come a principle this may be one,>
      text <For the declaring of our precious stone.>
    block
      text <For as of one masse was made all thing,>
      text <Right so in our practize must it be,>
      text <All our secreats of one Image must spring,>
      text <As in Philosophers bookes whoso list to see,>
      text <Our stone is called the lesse world, one and three;>
      text <Magnesa also of sulphure and Mercurie,>
      text <Proportionate by nature most perfectlie.>
    block
      text <But many one marueileth and maruaile may,>
      text <And museth on such a marueilous thing,>
      text <What is our stone; sith Philosophers say>
      text <To such as euer be it in seeking.>
      text <For foules and fisshes to vs doth it bring,>
      text <Euery man it hath, and it is in euery place,>
      text <In thee in me, and in each thing, time and space?>
    block
      text <To this I answere that Mercurie it is I wis,>
      text <But not the common called quicksiluer by name,>
      text <But Mercurie without which nothing being is,>
      text <All Philosophers record and truely saine the same,>
      text <But simple searchers putteth them in blame,>
      text <Saying they hid it but they be blame worthy,>
      text <Which be no Clearkes and meddle with Philosophy.>
    block
      text <But though it Mercurie be, yet wisely vnderstand,>
      text <Wherein it is, and where thou shalt it seech,>
      text <Else I counsell thee take not this work in hand,>
      text <For Philosophers flatter fooles with fayre speech:>
      text <But listen to me, for truly I will thee teach,>
      text <Which is this Mercurie most profitable,>
      text <Being to thee nothing deceiueable.>
    block
      text <It is more neere in some things than in some;>
      text <Therefore take heede what I to thee write>
      text <For if knowledge to thee neuer come,>
      text <Therefore yet shalt thou me not twite,>
      text <For I will truely now thee excite>
      text <To vnderstand well Mercuries three,>
      text <The keyes which of this science bee.>
    block
      text <Raymond his menstrues doth them call,>
      text <Without which truly no trueth is done:>
      text <But two of them be superficiall,>
      text <The third essentiall of Sunne and Moone,>
      text <Their properties I will declare right soone,>
      text <And Mercurie of mettalls essentiall,>
      text <Is the principle of our stone materiall.>
    block
      text <In Sunne and Moone our Menstrue is not seene,>
      text <It appeareth not but by effect to sight,>
      text <That is the stone of which we meene,>
      text <Who so our writings conceiueth aright,>
      text <It is a soule, a substance bright.>
      text <Of Sunne and Moone a subtill influence,>
      text <Whereby the earth receiueth resplendence.>
    block
      text <For what is Sunne and Moone sayth Auicen,>
      text <But earth which is pure white and red:>
      text <Take from it the said cleerenes, and then>
      text <That earth will stand but in little stead;>
      text <The whole compound is called our lead:>
      text <The qualitie of clearenes from Sun and Moone dooth come,>
      text <These are our menstrues both all and some.>
    block
      text <Bodies with the first we calcine naturally>
      text <Perfect, but none which been vncleene,>
      text <Except one which is vsually>
      text <Named by Philosophers the Lyon greene:>
      text <He is the meane the Sunne and Moone betweene>
      text <Of winning tincture with perfectnes,>
      text <As Geber thereunto beareth witnes.>
    block
      text <With the second which is an humiditie>
      text <Vegitable, reuiuing that earst was dead,>
      text <Both principles materials must loosed be>
      text <And formalls, els stand they little in stead:>
      text <These menstrews therefore know I thee reed,>
      text <Without the which neither true calcination>
      text <Done may be, not true dissolution.>
    block
      text <With the third humiditie most permanent,>
      text <Incombustible and vnctuous in his nature,>
      text <Hermes tree vnto ashes is brent,>
      text <It is our naturall fire most sure,>
      text <Our Mercurie, our Sulphur, our tincture pure,>
      text <Our soule, our stone borne vp with winde>
      text <In the earth ingendred, beare this in minde.>
    block
      text <This stone also tell thee I dare,>
      text <Is the vapour of mettalls potentiall,>
      text <How thou shalt get it, thou must beware,>
      text <For inuisible truely is this menstruall,>
      text <Howbeit with the second water philosophicall,>
      text <By separation of Elements it may appeare>
      text <To sight, in forme of water cleare.>
    block
      text <If this menstrue by labour exuberate>
      text <With it may be made Sulphur of nature,>
      text <If it be well and kindly acuate>
      text <And circulate into a spirit pure,>
      text <Then to dissolue thou must be sure,>
      text <Thy base with it in diuers wise,>
      text <As thou shalt know by thy practise.>
    block
      text <That poynt therefore in his due place,>
      text <I will declare with other moe,>
      text <If God will graunt me grace and space,>
      text <And me preserue in life from woe,>
      text <As I thee teach looke thou doe so:>
      text <And for the first ground principall,>
      text <Vnderstand thy waters menstruall.>
    block
      text <And when thou hast made Calcination,>
      text <Encreasing not wasting moysture radicall,>
      text <Vntill thy base by oft subtilation,>
      text <Will lightly flowe as wax vpon mettall,>
      text <Then loose it with thy vegetable menstruall,>
      text <Till thou haue oyle thereof in colour bright,>
      text <Then is that menstrue visible to sight.>
    block
      text <And oyle is drawne out in colour of golde,>
      text <Or like thereto out of fine red lead,>
      text <Which Raymond sayd when he was olde,>
      text <Much more than golde would stand in stead:>
      text <For when he was for age nigh dead,>
      text <He made thereof Aurum potabile,>
      text <Which him reuiued as men might see.>
    block
      text <For so together may they be circulate,>
      text <That is the base oyle and the vegetable menstruall,>
      text <So that it be by labour exuberate,>
      text <And made by craft a stone celestiall,>
      text <Of nature so firie that we it call,>
      text <Our Bazeliske or our Cockatrice,>
      text <Our great Elixer most of price.>
    block
      text <Which as the sight of Bazeliske his obiect>
      text <Killeth, so sleyeth it crude Mercurie,>
      text <When thereupon he is proiect,>
      text <In twinckle of an eye most sodainly,>
      text <That Mercurie then teineth permanently,>
      text <All bodies to Sunne and Moone perfect,>
      text <Thus guide thy base both red and white.>
    block
      text <Aurum potabile thus is made,>
      text <Of golde not commonly calcinate,>
      text <But of our tincture that will not fade,>
      text <Out of our base drawn with the menstrue circulate▪>
      text <But naturall calcination must algate>
      text <Be made, ere thy golde dissolued may bee,>
      text <That principle first therefore I will teach thee.>
    block
      text <But into chapters this Treatise I will diuide,>
      text <In number twelue with due recapitulation;>
      text <Superfluous rehearsalls Ile lay aside,>
      text <Intending onely to giue true information,>
      text <Both of theorick and practick operation:>
      text <That by my writing whoso guided will bee,>
      text <Of his intent perfectly speede shall hee.>
    block
      text <The first chapter shall be of naturall Calcination,>
      text <The second of Dissolution secreat and Philosophicall,>
      text <The third of our elementall Separation,>
      text <The fourth of Coniunction matrimoniall,>
      text <The fift of Putrifaction follow shall,>
      text <Of Congelation albificate shalbe the sixt,>
      text <Then of Cibation the seauenth shall follow next.>
    block
      text <The secret of Sublimation the eight shall show;>
      text <The ninth shall be of firmentation;>
      text <The tenth of our exaltation I trow;>
      text <The eleuenth of our meruailous multiplication;>
      text <The twelfth of proiection, then recapitulation:>
      text <And so this treatize shall take an end,>
      text <By the helpe of God as I intend.>

  text <Of Calcination. The first Gate.>
    block
      text <CAlcination is the purgation of our stone,>
      text <Restoring also of his naturall heate,>
      text <Of radicall humiditie it looseth none,>
      text <Inducing solution into our stone most meete,>
      text <After philosophie I you behight>
      text <Doo, but not after the common guise,>
      text <With Sulphures or Salts preparate in diuers wise.>
    block
      text <Neither with Corosiues nor with fire alone,>
      text <Neither with vineger nor with water ardent,>
      text <Nor with the vapour of leade our stone>
      text <Is calcined according to our intent:>
      text <All those to calcining which so be bent,>
      text <From this hard science withdrawe their hand,>
      text <Till they our calcining better vnderstand.>
    block
      text <For by such calcination their bodies be shent,>
      text <Which minisheth the moysture of our stone:>
      text <Therefore when bodies to powder be brent,>
      text <Dry as ashes of tree or bone,>
      text <Of such calxes then will we none;>
      text <For moysture we multiplie radicall,>
      text <In calcining minishing none at all.>
    block
      text <And for a sure ground of our true calcination,>
      text <Worke wittely only kind with kind:>
      text <For kind vnto kind hath appetitiue inclination,>
      text <Who knoweth not this in knowledge is blind,>
      text <He may foorth wander as mist in the wind,>
      text <Wotting neuer with profite where to light,>
      text <Because he conceaues not our words aright.>
    block
      text <Ioyne kind to kind therefore as reason is,>
      text <For euery burgeon answers his owne seede,>
      text <Man getteth man, a beast a beast I wis,>
      text <Further to treate of this it is no neede.>
      text <But vnderstand this poynt if thou wilt speede,>
      text <Each thing is first calcined in his owne kind;>
      text <This well conceaued fruite therein shalt thou finde.>
    block
      text <And we make Calx vnctuous both white and red>
      text <Of three degrees or our base be perfect,>
      text <Fluxible as waxe, els stand they in no sted.>
      text <By right long processe as Philosophers doo write,>
      text <A yeare we take or more to our respite:>
      text <For in lesse space our Calxes will not be made,>
      text <Able to teyne with colour that will not fade.>
    block
      text <And for thy proportion thou must beware,>
      text <For therein maist thou be beguil'd,>
      text <Therefore thy work that thou not mare,>
      text <Let thy bodie be subtilly fyl'de>
      text <With Mercury as much then so subtil'd,>
      text <One of the Sunne, two of the Moone,>
      text <Till altogether like papp be doone.>
    block
      text <Then make the Mercurie foure to the Sun▪>
      text <Two to the Moone as it should bee,>
      text <And thus thy worke must be begun,>
      text <In figure of the Trinitee,>
      text <Three of the bodie and of the spirite three,>
      text <And for the vnitie of the substance spirituall>
      text <One moe than of the substance corporall.>
    block
      text <By Raymonds reportory this is true,>
      text <Proportion there who list to looke,>
      text <The same my Doctor to me did shew,>
      text <But three of the spirite Bacon tooke,>
      text <To one of the bodie for which I a wooke,>
      text <Many a night ere I it wist.>
      text <And both be true take which you list.>
    block
      text <If the water also be equall in proportion>
      text <To the earth, with heate in due measure,>
      text <Of them shall spring a new burgeon,>
      text <Both white and red in pure tincture,>
      text <Which in the fire shall euer indure,>
      text <Kill thou the quick the dead reuiue;>
      text <Make trinitie vnitie without any striue.>
    block
      text <This is the surest and best proportion,>
      text <For there is least of the part spirituall,>
      text <The better therefore shall be solution,>
      text <Than if thou did it with water swall,>
      text <Thine earth ouer glutting which loseth all>
      text <Take heede therefore to potters loame,>
      text <And make thou neuer too neshe thy wombe.>
    block
      text <That loame beholde how it tempred is,>
      text <The meane also how it is calcinate,>
      text <And euer in minde looke thou beare this;>
      text <That neuer thine earth with water be suffocate,>
      text <Drye vp thy moysture with heate most temperate,>
      text <Help Dissolution with moysture of the Moone,>
      text <And Congelation with the Sunne, then hast thou doone.>
    block
      text <Foure Natures into the fift so shalt thou turne,>
      text <Which is a Nature most perfect and temperate,>
      text <But hard it is with thy bare foote to spurne>
      text <Against a barr of yron, or steele new acuate,>
      text <For many doe so which be infatuate,>
      text <When they such high things take in hand,>
      text <Which they in no wise doe vnderstand.>
    block
      text <In egges, in vitriall, or in blood,>
      text <What riches wend they there to finde,>
      text <If they Philosophy vnderstood,>
      text <They would not in working be so blinde;>
      text <Golde or siluer to seeke out of kinde:>
      text <For like as fire of burning principle is,>
      text <So is the principle of gilding gould I wis.>
    block
      text <If thou intend therefore for to make>
      text <Gold and Siluer by craft of our philosophie,>
      text <Thereto neyther egges nor bloud thou take>
      text <But Gold and Siluer which naturally>
      text <Calcined wisely and not manually,>
      text <A new generation will forth bring,>
      text <Encreasing their kinde as doth euery thing.>
    block
      text <And if it true were that profit might be>
      text <In things which be not mettaline,>
      text <In which be coulors pleasant to see,>
      text <As in bloud, eggs, haire, vrine. or wine,>
      text <Or in meane mineralls digd out of the myne,>
      text <Yet must that element be putrified and seperate,>
      text <And with Elements of perfect bodies be dispousate.>
    block
      text <But first of these elements make thou rotacion,>
      text <And into water thine earth turne first of all,>
      text <Then of thy water make ayre by leuigacion,>
      text <And ayre make fier, then Maister I will thee call>
      text <Of all our secrets great and small:>
      text <The wheele of Elements then canst thou turne about,>
      text <Truely conceiuing our writings without doubt.>
    block
      text <This done, goe backwards turning the wheele againe,>
      text <And into water turne thy fire anone,>
      text <Ayre into earth, els labourest thou in vaine,>
      text <For so to temperment is brought our stone,>
      text <And Natures contractions foure are made one,>
      text <After they haue three times been circulate,>
      text <And also thy base perfectly consumate.>
    block
      text <Thus vnder the moysture of the Moone,>
      text <And vnder the temperate heate of the Sunne,>
      text <Thine Elements shalbe incinerate soone,>
      text <And then thou hast the maistrie wonne:>
      text <Thanke God thy worke was then so begunne,>
      text <For there thou hast one token trewe,>
      text <Which first in blacknes to thee will shewe.>
    block
      text <The head of the Crowe that token call wee,>
      text <And some men call it the Crowes bill;>
      text <Some call it the ashes of Hermes tree,>
      text <And thus they name it after their will:>
      text <Our Toade of the earth which eateth his fill,>
      text <Some nameth it by which it is mortificate>
      text <The spirit with venome intoxicate.>
    block
      text <But it hath names I say to thee infinite,>
      text <For after each thing that blacknes is to sight,>
      text <Named it is till time it waxeth white,>
      text <Then hath it names of more delight,>
      text <After all things that been full white,>
      text <And the red likewise after the same,>
      text <Of all red things doth take the name.>
    block
      text <At the first gate now art thou in,>
      text <Of the Philosophers Castell where they dwell,>
      text <Proceede wisely that thou may winne>
      text <In at moe gates of that Castell,>
      text <Which Castell is round as any bell,>
      text <And gates it hath eleuen yet moe,>
      text <One is conquered, now to the second goe.>
    block
      text <The end of the first gate.>

  text <Of Dissolution. The second Gate.>
    block
      text <OF Dissolution now will I speake a word or two,>
      text <Which sheweth out what erst was hid frō sight,>
      text <And maketh intenuate things that were thicke also,>
      text <By vertue of our first menstrue cleare and bright,>
      text <In which our bodies eclipsed been of light,>
      text <And of their hard and drye compaction subtilate,>
      text <Into their owne first matter kindly retrogradate.>
    block
      text <One in gender they be, and in number two,>
      text <Whose Father is the Sunne, the Moone the Mother,>
      text <The Mouer is Mercurie, these and no moe>
      text <Be our Magnesia, our Adropp, and none other>
      text <Things here be, but onely sister and brother,>
      text <That is to meane agent and patient,>
      text <Sulphure and Mercury coessentiall to our intent.>
    block
      text <Betwixt these two equalitie contrarious,>
      text <Ingendred is a meane most marueilously,>
      text <Which is our Mercury and menstrue vnctuous,>
      text <Our secreat Sulphure working inuisibly,>
      text <More fiercely than fire burning the bodie,>
      text <Dissoluing the bodie into water minerall,>
      text <Which night for darknes in the North we doe call.>
    block
      text <But yet I trow thou vndestandst not vtterly,>
      text <The very secreat of the Philosophers Dissolution,>
      text <Therefore conceiue me I counsell thee wittily,>
      text <For the truth I will tell thee without delusion:>
      text <Our solution is cause of our Congelation;>
      text <For Dissolution on the one side corporall,>
      text <Causeth Congelation on the other side spirituall.>
    block
      text <And we dissolue into water which wetteth no hand,>
      text <For when the earth is integrately incinerate,>
      text <Then is the water congealed; this vnderstand>
      text <For the elements be so together concatenate,>
      text <That when the bodie is from his first forme alterate,>
      text <A new forme is induced immediatly,>
      text <For nothing being without all forme is vtterly.>
    block
      text <And heere a secret to thee I will disclose,>
      text <Which is the ground vnto our secrets all,>
      text <And it not knowne thou shalt but lose>
      text <Thy labour and costs both great and small,>
      text <Take heed therefore in error that thou not fall,>
      text <The more thine earth, and the lesse thy water be,>
      text <The rather and better solucion shalt thou see.>
    block
      text <Behold how yce to water doth relent,>
      text <And so it must for water it was before,>
      text <Right so againe to water our earth is went,>
      text <And water thereby congeald for euermore,>
      text <For after all Philosophers that euer were bore,>
      text <Each mettall was once water mynerall,>
      text <Therefore with water they turne to water all.>
    block
      text <In which water of kinde occasionate,>
      text <Of qualities been repugnant and diuersitie,>
      text <Things into things must therefore be rotate,>
      text <Vntill diuersitie be brought to perfect vnitie:>
      text <For Scripture recordeth when the earth shall be>
      text <Troubled, and into the deepe Sea shall be cast,>
      text <Mountaines and bodies likewise at the last.>
    block
      text <Our bodies be likened conueniently>
      text <To mountaines, which after high Planets we name,>
      text <Into the deepnes therefore of Mercurie>
      text <Turne them, and keepe thee out of blame,>
      text <For then shalt thou see a noble game,>
      text <How all shall become powder as soft as silke,>
      text <So doth our rennit kindly kurd vp our milke.>
    block
      text <Then hath the bodies their first forme lost,>
      text <And others been induced immediatly,>
      text <Then hast thou well bestowed thy cost:>
      text <Whereas others vncunning must goe by,>
      text <Not knowing the secrets of our philosohie:>
      text <Yet one poynt more I must tell thee,>
      text <How each bodie hath dimensions three.>
    block
      text <Altitude, Latitude, and also profunditie,>
      text <By which all gates turne we must our wheele,>
      text <Knowing that thine entrance in the West shall be,>
      text <Thy passages forth to the North if thou doo weele,>
      text <And there thy lights lose their lights each deele;>
      text <For there thou must abide by ninetie nights>
      text <In darknes of purgatorie withouten lights.>
    block
      text <Then take thy course vp to the East anone,>
      text <By colours passing variable in manifold wise,>
      text <And then be winter and vere nigh ouergone,>
      text <To the East therefore thine ascending deuise,>
      text <For there the Sunne with daylight doth vprise>
      text <In sommer, and there disport thee with delight,>
      text <For there thy worke shall become perfect white.>
    block
      text <Foorth from the East into the South ascend,>
      text <And set thee downe there in the chaire of fire,>
      text <For there is haruest, that is to say an end>
      text <Of all this worke after thine owne desire,>
      text <There shineth the Sunne vp in his Hemisphere,>
      text <After the Eclipses in rednes with glorie,>
      text <As king to raigne vpon all mettals and Mercurie.>
    block
      text <And in one glasse must be done all this thing,>
      text <Like to an Egge in shape and closed weele,>
      text <Then must thou know the measure of firing,>
      text <The which vnknowne thy worke is lost each deele:>
      text <Let neuer thy glasse be hotter than thou maist feele>
      text <And suffer still in thy bare hand to hold,>
      text <For feare of losing, as Philosophers haue told.>
    block
      text <Yet to my doctrine furthermore attend,>
      text <Beware thy glasse thou neuer open ne meue>
      text <From the beginning till thou haue made an end;>
      text <If thou doo contrarie, thy worke may neuer cheue.>
      text <Thus in this Chapter which is but briefe,>
      text <I haue thee taught thy true solution:>
      text <Now to the third gate goe, for this is won.>
    block
      text <The end of the second gate.>

  text <Of Seperation. The third gate.>
    block
      text <SEperation doth each part from other diuide,>
      text <The subtile from the grosse, the thick frō the thinn>
      text <But Seperation manuall looke thou set a side,>
      text <For that pertaines to fooles that little good doth winn,>
      text <But in our Seperation Nature doth not blinn,>
      text <Making diuision of qualities elementall,>
      text <Into a fift degree till they be turned all.>
    block
      text <Earth is turned into water vnder black and bloe,>
      text <And water after into ayre vnder very white,>
      text <Then Aire into fire, elements there be no moe,>
      text <Of these is made our stone of great delight,>
      text <But of this Seperation much more must we write,>
      text <And Seperation is called by Philosophers definition,>
      text <Of the saide foure elements terraptatiue dispersion.>
    block
      text <Of this Seperation I finde a like figure,>
      text <Thus spoken by the Prophet in the Psalmodie,>
      text <God brought out of a stone a flood of water pure,>
      text <And out of the hardest rock oyle abundantly,>
      text <So out of our stone precious if thou be witty,>
      text <Oyle incombustable, and water thou shalt draw,>
      text <And there abouts at the coale thou needst not to blow.>
    block
      text <Doe this with heate easie and nourishing,>
      text <First with moyst fire and after that with drie,>
      text <The flegme with patience out drawing,>
      text <And after that the other Natures wittely>
      text <Drye vp thine earth vntill it be thirsty,>
      text <By Calcination else labourest thou in vaine,>
      text <And then make it drink vp the moysture againe.>
    block
      text <Seperation thus must thou oftetimes make,>
      text <Thy waters diuiding into partes two,>
      text <So that the subtile from the grosse thou take,>
      text <Till earth remaine beneath in colours bloe,>
      text <That earth is fixed to abide all woe,>
      text <The other parte is spirituall and flying,>
      text <But thou must turne them all into one thing.>
    block
      text <Then oyle and water with water shall distill,>
      text <And through her helpe receiue mouing,>
      text <Keepe well these two that thou not spill>
      text <Thy worke for lack of due closing,>
      text <And make thy stopple of glasse melting,>
      text <The topp of thy vessell together with it,>
      text <Then Philosopher-like it is vp shit.>
    block
      text <The water wherewith thou mayst reuiue the stone,>
      text <Looke thou distill before thou worke with it,>
      text <Oftentimes by it selfe alone,>
      text <And by this sight thou shalt wit,>
      text <From feculent feces when it is quit:>
      text <For some men can with Saturne it multiplie,>
      text <And other substance which we defie.>
    block
      text <Distill it therefore till it be clene>
      text <And thinne like water as it should be,>
      text <As heauen in colour bright and shene,>
      text <Keping both figure and ponderositee,>
      text <Therewith did Hermes moysten his tree:>
      text <Within his glasse he made it grow vpright,>
      text <With flowers discoloured beautifull to sight.>
    block
      text <This water is like to the venymous Tire,>
      text <Wherewith the mighty triacle is wrought,>
      text <For it is poyson most strong of Ire,>
      text <A stronger poyson cannot be thought,>
      text <At Pothecaries often therefore it is sought,>
      text <But no man by it shalbe intoxicate,>
      text <From the time it is into medicine elixerate.>
    block
      text <For then as is the Triacle true,>
      text <It is of poyson most expulsiue,>
      text <And in his working doth marueiles shew,>
      text <Preseruing many from death to life,>
      text <But looke thou meddle it with no corosiue,>
      text <But choose it pure and quick rinning,>
      text <If thou thereby wilt haue winning.>
    block
      text <It is a marueilous thing in kinde,>
      text <And without it can nothing be done,>
      text <Therefore Hermes called it his winde,>
      text <For it is vp flying from Sunne and Moone,>
      text <And maketh our stone flie with it soone,>
      text <Reuiuing the dead and giuing life,>
      text <To Sunne and Moone, husband and wife.>
    block
      text <Which if they were not by craft made quick,>
      text <And their fatnes with water drawne out,>
      text <And so the thinne disseuered from the thick,>
      text <Thou shouldst neuer bring this worke about:>
      text <If thou wilt therefore speede without doubt,>
      text <Rayse vp the birds out of their neast,>
      text <And after againe bring them to rest.>
    block
      text <Water with water accord will and ascend,>
      text <And spirit with spirit, for they be of one kinde,>
      text <Which after they be exalted make to discend,>
      text <So shalt thou deuide that, which Nature erst did binde,>
      text <Mercury essentiall turning into winde,>
      text <Without which naturall and subtill Seperation,>
      text <May neuer be complete profitable generation.>
    block
      text <Now to helpe thee in at this gate,>
      text <The last secreat I will declare to thee,>
      text <Thy water must be seauen times sublimate,>
      text <Else shall no kindly Dissolution bee,>
      text <Nor putrifying shalt thou none see;>
      text <Like liquid pitch, nor colours appearing>
      text <For lack of fire within the glasse working.>
    block
      text <Foure fires there be which thou must vnderstand,>
      text <Naturall, innaturall, against Nature also,>
      text <And elementall which doth burne the brand:>
      text <These foure fires vse we and no moe,>
      text <Fire against nature must doe thy bodie woe,>
      text <This is our Dragon as I thee tell,>
      text <Fiercely burning as the fire of hell.>
    block
      text <Fire of nature is the third menstruall,>
      text <That fire is naturall in each thing;>
      text <But fire occasionate, we call vnnaturall,>
      text <As heate of ashes, and balnes for putrifying:>
      text <Without these fires thou maist naught bring>
      text <To Putrifaction, for to be seperate,>
      text <Thy matters together proportionate.>
    block
      text <Therefore make fire thy glasse within,>
      text <Which burneth the bodie much more than fire>
      text <Elementall, if thou wilt winne>
      text <Our secrets according to thy desire:>
      text <Then shall thy seeds both rot and spire>
      text <By helpe of fire occasionate,>
      text <That kindly after they may be seperate.>
    block
      text <Of Seperation the Gate must thus be wonne,>
      text <That furthermore yet thou maist proceed>
      text <Towards the Gate of secret Coniunction,>
      text <Into the Castle which will thee inner leed:>
      text <Doe after my counsell if thou wilt speed,>
      text <With two strong lockes this Gate is shir,>
      text <As consequently thou shalt well wit.>
    block
      text <The end of the third Gate.>

  text <Of Coniunction. The fourth Gate.>
    block
      text <AFter the Chapiter of naturall Seperation,>
      text <By which the elemēts of our stone disseuered be,>
      text <The chapter here followeth of secret Coniunction,>
      text <Which Natures repugnant ioyneth to perfect vnitie,>
      text <And so them knitteth that none from others may flie,>
      text <When they by fire shalbe examinate,>
      text <They be togethers so surely coniungate.>
    block
      text <And therefore Philosophers giue this definition>
      text <Saying this Coniunction is nothing els>
      text <But of disseuered qualities a copulation,>
      text <Or of principles a coequation as others tells:>
      text <But some men with Mercurie that Pothecaries sells>
      text <Medleth bodies, which cannot diuide>
      text <Their matter, and therefore they slip aside.>
    block
      text <For vntill the time the soule be seperate>
      text <And cleansed from his originall sinne>
      text <With the water, and throughly spiritualizate,>
      text <The true Coniunction maist thou neuer begin:>
      text <Therefore the soule first from the bodie twyne,>
      text <Then of the corporall part and of the spirituall.>
      text <The soule shall cause coniunction perpetuall.>
    block
      text <Of two Coniunctions Philosophers mencion make,>
      text <Grosse when the bodie with Mercury is reincrudate▪>
      text <But let this passe, and to the second heede take,>
      text <Which as I saide is after Seperation celebrate,>
      text <In which the parties be left with least to colligate,>
      text <And so promoted vnto most perfect temperance,>
      text <That neuer after amongst them may be repugnance.>
    block
      text <Thus causeth Seperation true Coniunction to be had,>
      text <Of water and ayre, with earth and fire,>
      text <But that each element into other may be lad,>
      text <And so abide for euer to thy desire,>
      text <Doe as doe dawbers with clay or myre,>
      text <Temper them thick and make them not too thinne,>
      text <So doe vpdrying, thou shalt the rather winne.>
    block
      text <But manners there be of our Coniunction three,>
      text <The first is called by Philosophers Diptatiue,>
      text <The which betwixt the agent and patient must be,>
      text <Male and female, Mercury, and Sulphure viue,>
      text <Matter, and forme, thinne, and thick to thrine,>
      text <This lesson will helpe thee without any doubt,>
      text <And our Coniunction truly to bring about.>
    block
      text <The second manner is called Triptatiue,>
      text <Which is Coniunction, made of things three,>
      text <Of bodie, soule and spirit, that they not striue,>
      text <Which trinitie thou must bring to vnitee,>
      text <For as the soule to the spirite the bond must bee;>
      text <Right so the bodie the soule to him must knit,>
      text <Out of thy minde let not this lesson flit.>
    block
      text <The third manner and also the last of all,>
      text <Foure Elements together which ioyne to abide,>
      text <Tetraptatiue certainely Philosophers doe it call,>
      text <And specially Guido de Montano whose fame goeth wide,>
      text <And therefore in most laudable maner this tide,>
      text <In our Coniunction foure Elements must aggregate>
      text <In due proportion, which first a sunder were seperate.>
    block
      text <Therefore like as the woman hath veines fifteene,>
      text <And the man but fiue to the act of their secunditie,>
      text <Required in our Coniunction first I meene,>
      text <So must the man our Sunne haue of his water three,>
      text <And nine his wife, which three to him must bee:>
      text <Then like with like will ioy haue for to dwell,>
      text <More of Coniunction me needeth not to tell.>
    block
      text <This chapiter I will conclude right soone therefore,>
      text <Grosse Coniunction charging thee to make but one,>
      text <For seldome haue strumpets children of them ybore,>
      text <And so thou shalt neuer come by our stone,>
      text <Without thou let the woman lig alone,>
      text <That after she once haue conceiued of the man,>
      text <Her Matrix be shut vp from all other than.>
    block
      text <For such as adde euer more crude to crude,>
      text <Opening their vessell letting their matters keele,>
      text <The sparme conceiued they nourish not but delude>
      text <Themselues, and sp•ll their worke each deele,>
      text <If thou therefore haue lift to doe weele,>
      text <Close vp thy Matrix and nourish the seede,>
      text <With heat continual and temperate if thou wilt speed.>
    block
      text <And when thy vessell hath stood by moneths fiue,>
      text <And clowdes and Eclipses be passed each one,>
      text <The light appearing, encrease thy heate then beliue,>
      text <Vntill bright and shining in whitenes be thy Stone▪>
      text <Then maist thou open thy glasse anone,>
      text <And feede thy childe which is ybore,>
      text <With milke and meate ay more and more.>
    block
      text <For now both moist and drie is so contemperate,>
      text <That of the water earth hath receiued impression,>
      text <Which neuer (after that) asunder may be seperate;>
      text <And right so water to earth hath giuen ingression,>
      text <That both together to dwell haue made profession,>
      text <And water of earth hath purchased a retentiue,>
      text <They foure made one neuer more to striue.>
    block
      text <Thus in two things all our intent doth hing,>
      text <In drie and moist, which be contraries two▪>
      text <In drie, that it the moyst to flixing bring,>
      text <In moist, that it giue liquefaction to the earth also:>
      text <Then of them thus a temperment may foorth goe,>
      text <A temperment not so thicke as the bodie is,>
      text <Neither so thinne as water withouten mis.>
    block
      text <Loosing and knitting thereof be principles two>
      text <Of this hard science, and poles most principall;>
      text <Howbeit that other principles be many moe,>
      text <As shining fanes, which show I shall:>
      text <Proceede therefore vnto another wall>
      text <Of this strong Castle of our wisdome,>
      text <That in at the fift Gate thou maist come.>
    block
      text <The end of the fourth Gate.>

  text <Of Putrifaction. The fift Gate.>
    block
      text <NOw we begin the chapter of Putrifaction,>
      text <Without which pole no seed may multiply,>
      text <Which must be done only by continual action>
      text <Of heate in the bodie, moyst not manually:>
      text <For bodies els may not be altred naturally,>
      text <Sith Christ doth witnes, without the graine of wheate>
      text <Dye in the ground, encrease maist thou none get.>
    block
      text <And in likewise without the matter putrifie,>
      text <It may in no wise truly be alterate,>
      text <Neither thy Elements may be diuided kindly,>
      text <Nor the coniunction of them perfectly celebrate:>
      text <That thy labor therefore be not frustrate,>
      text <The priuitie of our putrifying well vnderstand,>
      text <Or euer thou take this worke in hand.>
    block
      text <And Putrifaction may thus defined bee>
      text <After Philosophers sayings, to be of bodies the sleying;>
      text <And in our Compound a diuision of things three,>
      text <The killed bodies into corruption foorth leading,>
      text <And after vnto regeneration them abling,>
      text <For things being in the earth, without doubt>
      text <Be engendred of rotation of the heauens about.>
    block
      text <And therefore like as I haue sayd before,>
      text <Thine Elements commixt and wisely coequate,>
      text <Thou keepe in temperate heate eschewing euermore,>
      text <That they by violent heat be not incinerate>
      text <To powder drye vnprofitably Rubificate,>
      text <But into powder black as a crowes bill,>
      text <With heate of Balne or else of our dunghill.>
    block
      text <Vntill the time that nights be passed ninetie,>
      text <In moyst heate keepe them for any thing.>
      text <Soone after by blacknes thou shalt espie>
      text <That they draw fast to putrifying,>
      text <Which thou shalt after many colours bring>
      text <To perfect whitenes by patience easily,>
      text <And so thy seede in his nature shall multiplie.>
    block
      text <Make each the other then to halfe and kisse,>
      text <And like as children to play them vp and downe▪>
      text <And when their shirts are filed with pisse,>
      text <Then let the woman to wash be bowne,>
      text <Which oft for faintnes will fall in a swowne,>
      text <And dye at the last with her children all,>
      text <And goe to purgatorie to purge their filth originall.>
    block
      text <When they be there, by little and little increase>
      text <Their paines, by heat, aye more and more,>
      text <The fire from them let neuer cease.>
      text <And so that thy furnace be surely apt therefore,>
      text <Which wise men call an Athenore,>
      text <Conseruing heat required most temperatelie,>
      text <By which thy matter doth kindly putrifie.>
    block
      text <Of this principle speaketh sapient Guido,>
      text <And sayth by rotting dyeth the compound corporall,>
      text <And then after Morien and other moe,>
      text <Vpriseth againe regenerate simple and spirituall,>
      text <And were not heate and moysture continuall,>
      text <Sparme in the wombe might haue none abiding,>
      text <And so there should no fruite thereof vpspring.>
    block
      text <Therefore at the beginning our stone thou take,>
      text <And burie each one in other within their graue,>
      text <Then equally betwixt them a marriage make,>
      text <To ligge together sixe weekes let them haue,>
      text <Their seede conceiued, kindly to nourish and saue,>
      text <From the ground of their graue not rising that while,>
      text <Which secreat point doth many a one beguile.>
    block
      text <This time of conception with easie heate abide,>
      text <The blacknes shewing shall tell thee when they dye,>
      text <For they togeather like liquid pitch that tide,>
      text <Shall swell and burble, settle and putrifie,>
      text <Shining colours therin thou shalt espie,>
      text <Like to the rainebow marueilous to sight,>
      text <The Water then beginneth to drye vpright.>
    block
      text <For in moyst bodies heate working temperate,>
      text <Ingendreth blacknes, first of all which is,>
      text <Of kindly Coniunction the token assignate,>
      text <And of true putrifying: remember this,>
      text <For then perfectly to alter thou canst not misse,>
      text <And thus by the gate of blacknes thou must come in,>
      text <The light of Paradice in whitenes if thou wilt win.>
    block
      text <For first the Sunne in his vprising obscurate>
      text <Shalbe, and passe the waters of Noes flood,>
      text <On earth which was an hundreth dayes continuate>
      text <And fiftie, away ere all these waters yood;>
      text <Right so our waters (as wisemen vnderstood)>
      text <Shall passe, that thou with Dauid may say,>
      text <Abierunt in sicco flumina: beare this away.>
    block
      text <Soone after that Noah planted his vineyard,>
      text <Which royally flourished, and brought foorth grapes anone,>
      text <After which space thou shalt not be afeard,>
      text <For in likewise shal follow the flourishing of our stone:>
      text <And soone after that xxx. dayes be gone,>
      text <Thou shalt haue grapes right as Rubie read,>
      text <Which is our Adropp, our Vcifer, and our red lead.>
    block
      text <For like as soules after paines transitorie>
      text <Be brought to Paradice, where euer is ioyfull life;>
      text <So shall our Stone (after his darknes in Purgatorie)>
      text <Be purged, and ioyned in Elements withouten strife,>
      text <Reioyce the whitenes and beautie of his wife,>
      text <And passe from darknes of purgatorie to light>
      text <Of Paradice, in whitenes Elixer of great might.>
    block
      text <And that thou maist the rather to Putrifaction win,>
      text <This example thou take to thee for a true conclusion,>
      text <For all the secret of Putrifaction resteth therein;>
      text <The hart of oke that hath of water continuall infusion>
      text <Will not soone putrifie, I tell thee without delusion:>
      text <For though it in water lay 100. yeares and more.>
      text <Yet shouldst thou finde it sound as ere it was before.>
    block
      text <But and thou keepe it sometime wet & sometime drie,>
      text <As thou maist see in timber by vsuall experiment,>
      text <By processe of time that oke shall putrifie;>
      text <And so euen likewise according to our intent,>
      text <Sometime our tree must with the Sunne be brent,>
      text <And then with water we must it keele,>
      text <That by this meanes to rotting we may bring it weele.>
    block
      text <For now in wet, and now againe in drie,>
      text <And now in heate, and now againe in colde>
      text <To be, shall cause it soone to putrifie,>
      text <And so shalt thou bring to rotting thy golde:>
      text <Intreate thy bodies as I haue thee tolde,>
      text <And in thy putrifying, with heate be not too swift,>
      text <Least in the ashes thou seeke after thy thrift.>
    block
      text <Therefore thy water out of the earth thou drawe,>
      text <And make the soule therewith for to ascend;>
      text <Then downe againe into the earth it throwe,>
      text <That they oft times so ascend and descend:>
      text <From violent heate and sudden colde defend>
      text <Thy glasse, and make thy fire so temperate,>
      text <That by the sides the matter be not vitrificate.>
    block
      text <And be thou wise in choosing of the matter,>
      text <Meddle with no salts, sulphurs, nor meane mineralls:>
      text <For whatsoeuer any worker to thee doth clatter,>
      text <Our Sulphur and our Mercury been onely in metttalls,>
      text <Which oyles and waters some men them calls,>
      text <Foules and birds, with other names many one,>
      text <Because that fooles should neuer know our stone.>
    block
      text <For of this world our stone is called the sement>
      text <Which moued by craft as nature doth require,>
      text <In his encrease shall be full opulent,>
      text <And multiply his kinde after thine owne desire,>
      text <Therefore if God vouchsafe thee to inspire,>
      text <To know the truth, and fansies to eschew>
      text <Like vnto thee in riches shall be but few.>
    block
      text <But many men be moou'd to worke after their fantasie,>
      text <In many subiects in which be tinctures gay:>
      text <Both white and red diuided manually>
      text <To sight, but in the fire they flyeaway:>
      text <Such breake pottes and glasses day by day,>
      text <Enpoysoning themselues and loosing their sights,>
      text <With odours, smoakes, and watching vp by nights.>
    block
      text <Their clothes be baudy and worne thread bare,>
      text <Men may them smell for multipliers where they goe,>
      text <To file their fingers with corosiues they doo not spare,>
      text <Their eyes be bleard, their cheekes leane and blowe,>
      text <And thus for had I wist they suffer losse and woe:>
      text <And such when they haue lost that was in their purse,>
      text <Then doo they chide, and Philosophers sore doo curse.>
    block
      text <To see their houses it is a noble sport,>
      text <What furnaces, what glasses there be of diuers shapes,>
      text <What salts, what powders, what oyles, waters fort,>
      text <How eloquently de Materia prima their tungs do clap,>
      text <And yet to finde the truthe they haue no hap;>
      text <Of our Mercurie they meddle & of our sulphure viue,>
      text <Wherein they dote, and more and more vnthriue.>
    block
      text <For all the while they haue Philosophers bene,>
      text <Yet could they neuer know what was our Stone,>
      text <Some sought it in dung, in vrine, some in wine,>
      text <Some in starre slyme (for thing it is but one),>
      text <In blood, in egges: some till their thrift was gone,>
      text <Diuiding Elements, and breaking manie a pot,>
      text <Sheards multiplying, but yet they hit it not.>
    block
      text <They talke of the red man and of his white wife,>
      text <That is a speciall thing, and of the Elixers two,>
      text <Of the Quintessence, and of the Elixer of life,>
      text <Of honie, Celidonie, and of Secondines also,>
      text <These they diuide into Elements, with others moe;>
      text <No multipliers, but Philosophers called will they bee,>
      text <Which naturall Philosophie did neuer read nor see.>
    block
      text <This fellowship knoweth our Stone right weele,>
      text <They thinke them richer than is the King,>
      text <They will him help, he shall not faile>
      text <Fraunce for to winne a wondrous thing,>
      text <The holy Crosse home will they bring,>
      text <And if the King were prisoner ytake,>
      text <Right soone his raunsome would they make.>
    block
      text <A meruaile it is that Westminster Kerke,>
      text <To the which these Philosophers doo much haunt,>
      text <Since they can so much riches werke>
      text <As they make boast of and auaunt,>
      text <Drinking daylie at the wine a due taunt,>
      text <Is not made vp perfectly at once;>
      text <For truly it lacketh yet many stones.>
    block
      text <Fooles doo follow them at the taile,>
      text <Promoted to riches weening to bee;>
      text <But will you heare, what worship and auaile>
      text <They winne in London that noble Citie?>
      text <With siluer maces (as you may see)>
      text <Sergeants awaiteth on them each bowre,>
      text <So been they men of great honour.>
    block
      text <Sergeants seeke them from streete to streete,>
      text <Merchants and Goldsmiths lay after them watch,>
      text <That well is him that with them may meete,>
      text <For the great aduantage that they doe catch,>
      text <They hunt about as doth a bratch,>
      text <Weening to winne so great treasure,>
      text <That euer in riches they shall endure.>
    block
      text <Some would catch their goods againe,>
      text <And some more good would aduenture,>
      text <Some for to haue would be full faine>
      text <Of ten pounds one, I you ensure,>
      text <Some which haue lent without measure>
      text <Their goods, and be with pouertie clad,>
      text <To catch a noble, would be full glad.>
    block
      text <But when the Sergeants doth them arrest,>
      text <Their pautners be stuffed with Paris balls,>
      text <Or with signets of Saint Martins at the least;>
      text <But as for money it is pist against the walls:>
      text <Then be they led (as well for them befalls)>
      text <To Newgate or Ludgate as I you tell,>
      text <Because they shall in safegard dwell.>
    block
      text <Where is my money become, saith one?>
      text <And where is mine, saith he and he?>
      text <But will you heare how subtill they be anone>
      text <In answering, that they excused be?>
      text <Saying, of our Elixers robbed be we,>
      text <Else might we haue paid you all your golde,>
      text <Though it had been more by tenne folde.>
    block
      text <And then their Creditors they flatter so,>
      text <Promising to worke for them againe>
      text <In right short space the Elixers two,>
      text <Doting the Merchants that they be faine>
      text <To let them goe, but euer in vaine;>
      text <They worke so long, till at the last,>
      text <They be againe in prison cast.>
    block
      text <If any them aske, why they be not ritch?>
      text <They say they can make fine golde of tinne,>
      text <But he (say they) may surely swimme the ditch,>
      text <Which is vpholden by the chinne;>
      text <We haue no stock, therefore may we not winne,>
      text <Which if we had, we would soone werck>
      text <Inough to finish vp Westminster Kerck.>
    block
      text <And some of them be so deuout,>
      text <They will not dwell out of that place;>
      text <For there they may withouten doubt>
      text <Doe what them list to their solace,>
      text <The Archdeacon is so full of grace,>
      text <That if they blesse him with their crosse,>
      text <He forceth little of other mens losse.>
    block
      text <And when they there sit at the wine,>
      text <These Monkes they say haue manie a pound,>
      text <Would God (saith one) that some were mine.>
      text <Yet care away, let the cup goe round;>
      text <Drinke on saith another, the meane is found,>
      text <I am a maister of that Arte,>
      text <I warrant vs we shall haue part.>
    block
      text <Such causeth Monkes euill to doone,>
      text <To waste their wages through their dotage,>
      text <Some bringeth a mazer, and some a spoone,>
      text <Their Philosophers giueth them such comage,>
      text <Behighting them winning with domage,>
      text <A pound for a penie at the least againe;>
      text <And so faire promises make fooles faine.>
    block
      text <A royall medicine one vpon twelue,>
      text <They promise them thereof to haue,>
      text <Which they could neuer for them-selue>
      text <Yet bring about, so God me saue:>
      text <Beware such Philosophers no man depraue,>
      text <Which helpe these Monkes to riches so,>
      text <In thread bare coates that they must goe.>
    block
      text <The Abbot ought well to cherish this companie,>
      text <For they can teach his Monkes to liue in pouertie,>
      text <And to goe cloathed and moneyed religiouslie,>
      text <As did Saint Bennet, eschuing superfluitie,>
      text <Easing them also of the ponderositie>
      text <Of their purses, with pounds so aggrauate,>
      text <Which by Philosophie be now alleuiate.>
    block
      text <Lo who so medleth with this rich companie,>
      text <Great boast of their winning they may make:>
      text <For they shall reape as much by their Philosophie,>
      text <As they of the taile of an ape, can take:>
      text <Beware therefore for Iesus sake,>
      text <And meddle with nothing of great cost,>
      text <For if thou doe, it is but lost.>
    block
      text <These Philosophers (of which I spake before)>
      text <Meddle and blunder with manie a thing,>
      text <Running in errours euer more and more,>
      text <For lacke of true vnderstanding:>
      text <But like must like alwaies forth bring,>
      text <So hath God ordained in euerie kinde;>
      text <Would Iesus they would beare this in minde.>
    block
      text <Weene they of a Nettle to haue a Rose,>
      text <Or of an Elder to haue an apple sweete:>
      text <Alas, that wisemen their goods should lose,>
      text <Trusting such lorrells when they them meete,>
      text <Which say our Stone is troden vnder feete,>
      text <And maketh them vile things to distill,>
      text <Till all their howses with stench they fill.>
    block
      text <Some of them neuer learned a word in Schooles,>
      text <Should such by reason vnderstand Philosophie?>
      text <Be they Philosophers? Nay, they be fooles:>
      text <For their workes proue them vnwittie,>
      text <Meddle not with them, if thou be happie;>
      text <Least with their flatterie they so thee till,>
      text <That thou agree vnto their will.>
    block
      text <Spend not thy money away in waste,>
      text <Giue not to euery spirit credence,>
      text <But first examine, groape, and taste;>
      text <And as thou proouest, so put thy confidence,>
      text <But euer beware of great expence:>
      text <And if the Philosopher doe liue vertuouslie,>
      text <The better thou maist trust his Philosophie.>
    block
      text <Prooue him first, and him appose>
      text <Of all the secrets of our Stone;>
      text <Which if he knowe not, thou need not to lose,>
      text <Meddle thou no further, but let him gone,>
      text <Make he neuer so piteous a mone;>
      text <For then the Fox can fagge and faine,>
      text <When he would to his pray attaine.>
    block
      text <If he can answere as a Clarke,>
      text <Howbeit he hath not prooued it indeed,>
      text <And thou then help him to his warke;>
      text <If he be vertuous I hold it meed,>
      text <For he will thee quite if euer he speed,>
      text <And thou shalt knowe by a little anone,>
      text <If he haue knowledge of our Stone.>
    block
      text <One thing, one glasse, one furnace, and no moe,>
      text <Behold this principle if he doe take,>
      text <And if he doe not, then let him goe,>
      text <For he shall neuer thee rich man make;>
      text <Timely it is better thou him forsake,>
      text <Than after with losse and variance,>
      text <And other manner of displeasance.>
    block
      text <But if God fortune thee to haue>
      text <This Science by doctrine which I haue told,>
      text <Discouer it not whosoeuer it craue,>
      text <For fauour, feare, siluer, or gold;>
      text <Be no oppressor, letcher nor boaster bold:>
      text <Serue thy God, and help the poore among,>
      text <If thou this life lift to continue long.>
    block
      text <Vnto thy selfe thy secrets euer keepe>
      text <From sinners, which haue not God in dread,>
      text <But will thee cast in prison deepe,>
      text <Till thou them teach to doe it indeed,>
      text <Then slaunder on thee shall spring and spread,>
      text <That thou doest coyne then will they say,>
      text <And so vndoe thee for euer and aye.>
    block
      text <And if thou teach them this cunning,>
      text <Their sinfull liuing for to maintaine,>
      text <In hell therefore shalbe thy woonning,>
      text <For God of thee and them will take disdaine:>
      text <As thou nought couldst therefore thee faine,>
      text <That bodie and soule thou maist both saue,>
      text <And here in peace thy liuing to haue.>
    block
      text <Now in this Chapter I haue thee taught,>
      text <How thou thy bodies must putrifie,>
      text <And so to guide thee that thou be not caught,>
      text <And put to durance losse or villanie>
      text <My doctrine therefore remember wittely,>
      text <And passe forth towards the sixt Gate,>
      text <For thus the fift is triumphate.>
    block
      text <The end of the fift Gate.>

  text <Of Congelation. The sixt Gate.>
    block
      text <OF Congelation I need not much to write:>
      text <But what it is, I will to thee declare;>
      text <It is of soft things induration of colour white,>
      text <And confixation of spirits which flying are;>
      text <How to congeale, he needeth not much to care,>
      text <For Elements will knit together soone,>
      text <So that Putrifaction be kindly doone.>
    block
      text <But Congelations be made in diuers wise,>
      text <Of spirits and bodies dissolued to water cleare,>
      text <Of salts also dissolued twice or thrise,>
      text <And then congeald into a fluxible matter;>
      text <Of such congealing, fooles fast doo clatter,>
      text <And some dissolueth diuiding manuallie>
      text <Elements them after congealing to powder drie.>
    block
      text <But such congealing is not to our desire,>
      text <For vnto ours it is contrarious,>
      text <Our congelation dreadeth not the fire:>
      text <For it must euer stand in it vnctuous,>
      text <And it is also a tincture so bounteous,>
      text <Which in the aire congealed will not relent>
      text <To water, for then our worke were shent.>
    block
      text <Moreouer congeale not into so hard a stone>
      text <As glasse or christall, which melteth by fusion,>
      text <But so that it like waxe will melt anone>
      text <Withouten blast: and beware of delusion,>
      text <For such congealing accordeth not to our conclusion>
      text <As will not flowe, but runne to water againe>
      text <Like salt congealed, then labourest thou in vaine.>
    block
      text <Which congelation auaileth vs not a deale,>
      text <It longeth to multipliers, congealing vulgarly:>
      text <If thou therefore list to doe weele>
      text <(Sith the medicine shall neuer flowe kindly,>
      text <Neither congeale, without thou first it putrifie)>
      text <First purge, and then fixe the elements of our stone,>
      text <Till they together congeale and flowe anone.>
    block
      text <For when thy matter is made perfectly white,>
      text <Then will the spirit with the bodie congealed be:>
      text <But of that time thou maist haue long respite>
      text <Or it congeale like pearles in sight to thee,>
      text <Such congel••••n be thou glad to see,>
      text <And after lik• graines red as blood,>
      text <Richer than any worldly good.>
    block
      text <The earthly grosenes therefore first mortified,>
      text <In moysture blacknes ingendred is;>
      text <This principle may not be denied,>
      text <For naturall Philosophers so sayne ywis:>
      text <Which had, of whitenes thou maist not mis;>
      text <And into whitenes if thou congeale it once,>
      text <Then hast thou a stone most precious of all stones.>
    block
      text <And by the drie like as the moist did putrifie,>
      text <Which caused in colour blacknes to appeare,>
      text <Right so the moyst congealed by the drie,>
      text <Ingendreth whitenes shining by night full cleare,>
      text <And drines proceedeth as whiteth the matter,>
      text <Like as in blacknes moysture doth him shew>
      text <By colours variant alwayes new and new.>
    block
      text <The cause of all this is heate most temperate,>
      text <Working and mouing the matter continually,>
      text <And thereby also the matter is alterate,>
      text <Both inward and outward substantially,>
      text <Not as doo fooles to sight sophistically:>
      text <But in euerie part all fire to endure,>
      text <Fluxible, fixt, and stable in tincture.>
    block
      text <As Phisicke determineth of each digestion,>
      text <First done in the stomach in which is drines,>
      text <Causing whitenes without question,>
      text <Like as the second digestion causeth rednes,>
      text <Complete in the liuer by heate in temperatenes,>
      text <Right so our Stone by drines and by heate>
      text <Digested is to white and red compleate.>
    block
      text <But here thou must another secret knowe,>
      text <How the Philosophers childe in the ayre is borne,>
      text <Busie thee not too fast at the coale to blowe,>
      text <And take this neither for mocke nor scorne,>
      text <But trust me truly, else is all thy worke forlorne,>
      text <Without thine earth with water reuiued bee,>
      text <Our true congealing shalt thou neuer see.>
    block
      text <A soule it is betwixt heauen and earth being,>
      text <Arising from the earth as ayre with water pure,>
      text <And causing life in euerie liuely thing,>
      text <Incessable running vpon our foure folde nature,>
      text <Enforcing to better him with all his cure,>
      text <Which ayre is the fire of our Philosophie,>
      text <Named now oyle, now water mysticallie.>
    block
      text <And this meane ayre which oyle or water we call,>
      text <Our fire, our oyntment, our spirit, and our Stone,>
      text <In which one thing we ground our wisedomes all,>
      text <Goeth neither in nor out alone,>
      text <Nor the fire but the water anone:>
      text <First it out leadeth, and after it bringeth it in,>
      text <As water with water which will not lightly twin.>
    block
      text <And so may water only our water meeue,>
      text <Which mouing causeth both death and life>
      text <And water to water doth kindly cleeue>
      text <Without repugnance or anie strife,>
      text <Which water to fooles is nothing rife,>
      text <Being of the kinde withouten doubt>
      text <Of the spirit, called water and leader out.>
    block
      text <And water is the secret and life of euery thing,>
      text <That is of substance in this world yfound,>
      text <For of water each thing hath his beginning,>
      text <As showeth in women when they shalbe vnbound>
      text <By water, which passeth before if all be sound,>
      text <Called Albien, first from them running,>
      text <With greeuous throwes before their childing.>
    block
      text <And truly that is the cause most principall>
      text <Why Philosophers charge vs to be patient,>
      text <Till time the water be dried to powder all>
      text <With nourishing heate, continuall, not violent:>
      text <For qualities be contrarious of euerie element,>
      text <Till after blacke in white be made an vnion>
      text <Of them for euer, congeald without diuision.>
    block
      text <And furthermore, the preparation of this conuersion:>
      text <From thing to thing, from one state to another,>
      text <Is done onely by kindly and discreete operation>
      text <Of Nature, as is of sperme within the mother;>
      text <For sperme and heate, are as sister and brother,>
      text <Which be conuerted in themselues as nature can,>
      text <By action and passion at last to perfect man:>
    block
      text <For as the bodily part by nature was combyn•te>
      text <Into man, is such as the beginner was▪>
      text <Which though it thus frō thing to thing was alterate>
      text <Not out of kinde, to mixe with other kinde did passe,>
      text <And so our matter spermaticall within our glasse,>
      text <Within it selfe must turne from thing to thing▪>
      text <By heate most temperate only it nourishing.>
    block
      text <An other example naturall I may thee tell,>
      text <How the substance of an egge by nature is wrought>
      text <Into a Chicken not passing out of the shell,>
      text <A plainer example could I not haue thought,>
      text <And their conuersions be made till forth be brought>
      text <From state to state, the like by like in kinde,>
      text <With nourishing heate: onely beare this in minde.>
    block
      text <Another example here also thou maist read>
      text <Of vegetable things, taking consideration,>
      text <How euerie thing groweth of his owne seede>
      text <Through heate and moysture, by naturall operation;>
      text <And therfore myneralls be nourished by ministration>
      text <Of moysture radicall, which there beginning was,>
      text <Not passing their kinde within one glas.>
    block
      text <There we them turne from thing to thing againe,>
      text <Into their mother the water when they goe:>
      text <Which principle vnknowen, thou labourest in vaine.>
      text <Then all is sperme; and things there be no moe>
      text <But kinde with kinde in number two,>
      text <Male and female, agent and patient,>
      text <Within the matrix of the earth most orient.>
    block
      text <And these be turned by heate from thing to thing>
      text <Within one glasse, and so from state to state,>
      text <Vntill the time that nature doth them bring>
      text <Into one substance of the water regenerate:>
      text <And so the sperme with his kinde is alterate,>
      text <Able in likenes his kinde to multiply,>
      text <As doth in kinde all other things naturally.>
    block
      text <In the time of this said proces naturall,>
      text <While that the sperme conceiued is growing,>
      text <The substance is nourished with his owne menstruall,>
      text <Which water only out of the earth did spring,>
      text <Whose colour is greene in the first showing:>
      text <And from that time the Sunne hid•th his light,>
      text <Taking his course throughout the North by night.>
    block
      text <The sayd menstruall is (I say to thee in counsell)>
      text <The blood of our greene Lyon and not of vitriall▪>
      text <Dame Venus can the troth of this thee tell,>
      text <At the beginning, to counsell if thou her call,>
      text <This secret is hid by Philosophers great and small,>
      text <Which blood drawne out of the greene Lyon,>
      text <For lack of heate had not perfect digestion.>
    block
      text <But this blood called our secreat menstruall,>
      text <Wherewith our sperme is nourished temperately,>
      text <When it is turned into the feces corporall,>
      text <And so become white perfectly and very drye,>
      text <Congeald and fixed into his owne bodie,>
      text <Then biscoct blood to sight it may well seeme,>
      text <Of this worke named the milke white Dyademe.>
    block
      text <Vnderstand now that our firie water thus acuate,>
      text <Is called our menstruall water, wherein>
      text <Our earth is loosed and naturally calcinate,>
      text <By Congelation that they may neuer twinne,>
      text <But yet to congeale more water thou may not linne:>
      text <Into three partes of the acuate water sayd afore,>
      text <With the fourth parte of the earth congealed and no more.>
    block
      text <Vnto that substance therefore so congelate,>
      text <The fourth parte put of water christaline,>
      text <And make them then together to be dispousate,>
      text <By Congelation into a miner metaline,>
      text <Which like a sworde new slipped will shine,>
      text <After the blacknes which first will shew,>
      text <The fourth parte then giue it of water new.>
    block
      text <Imbibitions many it must haue yet,>
      text <Giue it the second, and after the third also.>
      text <The sayd proportion keeping in thy witt,>
      text <Then to another the fourth time looke thou goe,>
      text <The fift time and the sixt passe not therefore,>
      text <But put two partes at each time of them three,>
      text <And at the seuenth time fiue partes must there bee.>
    block
      text <When thou hast made seauen times Imbibition,>
      text <Againe then must thou turne about thy wheele,>
      text <And putrifie all that matter without addition,>
      text <First blacknes abiding if thou wilt doe weele,>
      text <Then into whitenes congeale it vp each deele,>
      text <And after by rednes into the south ascend,>
      text <Then hast thou brought thy base vnto an end.>
    block
      text <Thus is thy water then diuided into partes two,>
      text <With the first parte the bodies be putrificate,>
      text <And to thine Imbibitions the second parte must goe,>
      text <With which thy matter is afterwarde demigrate,>
      text <And soone vpon easie decoction albificate,>
      text <Then is it named by Philosophers out starry stone,>
      text <Bring that to rednes then is the sixt gate wonne.>
    block
      text <The end of the sixt gate.>

  text <Of Cibation. The seuenth Gate.>
    block
      text <NOw of Cibation I turne my pen to write,>
      text <Sith it must here the seuenth place occupie:>
      text <But in few words it wilbe expedite,>
      text <Take heede therefore, and vnderstand me wittelie;>
      text <Cibation is called a feeding of our matter drie,>
      text <With milke and meate, which moderately thou doe,>
      text <Vntill it be brought the third order vnto.>
    block
      text <But giue it neuer so much, that thou it glut;>
      text <Beware of dropsey, and also of Noahs flood:>
      text <By little and little therefore thou to it put>
      text <Of meate and drinke, as seemes to doo it good,>
      text <That watry humours not ouergrow the blood,>
      text <To drinke therefore let it be measured so,>
      text <That kindly appetite thou neuer quench it fro.>
    block
      text <For if it drinke too much, then must it haue>
      text <A vomit or els it wilbe sick too long,>
      text <From the dropsie therefore thy wombe thou saue,>
      text <And from the fl•x, or els it wilbe wrong,>
      text <But rather let it thirst for drinke among,>
      text <Than thou shouldst giue it ouermuch at once.>
      text <Which must in youth be dieted for the nonce.>
    block
      text <And if thou diet it (as nature doth require)>
      text <Moderately, till time that it be growen to age,>
      text <From colde it keeping, and nourishing with moyst fire,>
      text <Then shall it growe, and wexe full of courage,>
      text <And doe to thee both pleasure and aduantage:>
      text <For he shall make darke bodies whole and bright,>
      text <Clensing their leprosies through his might.>
    block
      text <Three times must thou turne about thy wheele,>
      text <Still keeping the rule of the said Cibation,>
      text <And then as soone as it the fire doth feele,>
      text <Like waxe it wilbe readie vnto liquation:>
      text <This chapter needeth no longer protestation,>
      text <For I haue tolde thee the dietorie most conuenient,>
      text <After thine Elements be made equipolent.>
    block
      text <And also how to whitenes thou shalt bring thy golde,>
      text <Most like in figure to leaues of hawthorne tree>
      text <Called Magnesia, afore as I haue tolde,>
      text <And our white Sulphure without combustibilitie,>
      text <Which from the fire away will neuer flie.>
      text <And thus the seuenth Gate (as you desired)>
      text <In the vprising of the Sunne is conquered.>
    block
      text <The end of the seuenth Gate.>

  text <Of Sublimation. The eight Gate.>
    block
      text <HEre of our Sublimation a word or two>
      text <I haue to speake, which the eight Gate is.>
      text <Fooles doo sublime, but sublime thou not so,>
      text <For we sublime not as they doe ywis:>
      text <To sublime truly therefore thou shalt not mis,>
      text <If thou canst make thy bodies first spirituall,>
      text <And then thy spirits (as I haue taught thee) corporall.>
    block
      text <Some doe Mercurie from vitrioll and salt sublime,>
      text <And other spirits from scales of yron and steele,>
      text <From egg-shels calcined, and from quick lime,>
      text <And in their manner yet sublime they right weele:>
      text <But such subliming accordeth neuer a deele>
      text <To our intents, for we sublime not so,>
      text <To true subliming therefore, now will I goe.>
    block
      text <In Sublimation first beware of one thing,>
      text <That thou sublime to the top of the vessell:>
      text <For without violence thou shalt it not downe bring>
      text <Againe, but there it will abide and dwell,>
      text <So it reioyceth with refrigeration I thee tell,>
      text <Keepe it therefore with temperate heate adowne>
      text <Full fortie dayes, till it wexe blacke and browne.>
    block
      text <For then the soule beginneth to come out>
      text <From his owne veynes, for all that subtill is>
      text <Will with the spirite ascend withouten doubt,>
      text <Beare in thy minde therefore, and thinke on this,>
      text <How here eclipsed been thy bodies,>
      text <As they doe putrifie subliming more and more>
      text <Into water, vntill they be all vp ybore.>
    block
      text <And thus their venome when they haue spued out>
      text <Into the water then blacke it doth appeare,>
      text <Becomming spirituall each deale without doubt,>
      text <Subliming easilie in our manner,>
      text <Into the water, which doth him beare:>
      text <For in the ayre our childe must thus be bore>
      text <Of the water againe, as I haue said before.>
    block
      text <But when these two by Sublimation continuall>
      text <Be laboured so with heate both moyst and temperate,>
      text <That all is white and purely made spirituall,>
      text <Then heauen vpon earth must be reiterate>
      text <Vntill the soule with the bodie be incorporate>
      text <That earth become all that before was heauen,>
      text <Which wilbe done in Sublimations seauen.>
    block
      text <And Sublimations we make for causes three,>
      text <The first cause is, to make the bodie spirituall;>
      text <The second is, that the spirite may corpora•l bee,>
      text <And become fixt with it, and consubstantiall;>
      text <The third cause is, that from his filthie originall>
      text <He may be cleansed, and his saltnes sulphurious>
      text <May be minished in him, which is infectious.>
    block
      text <Then when they thus together depured be,>
      text <They will sublime vp whiter than the snowe▪>
      text <That sight will greatly comfort thee:>
      text <For then anon perfectly thou shalt knowe>
      text <The spirits shall so adowne ythrowe,>
      text <That this eight Gate shalbe to thee vnlocked,>
      text <Out of the which many be shut and mocked.>
    block
      text <The end of the eight Gate.>

  text <Of Firmentation. The ninth Gate.>
    block
      text <TRue Firmentation few Workers vnderstand,>
      text <That secret therefore I will expound to thee,>
      text <I trauailed truly through manie a Land,>
      text <Ere euer I might finde any that would tell it mee:>
      text <Yet as God would, euermore blessed be hee,>
      text <At the last I came to the knowledge thereof perfite,>
      text <Take heede therefore what I thereof doe write.>
    block
      text <Firmentations in diuers manners be doone,>
      text <By which our medicine must be perpetuate>
      text <Into cleere water: some looseth Sunne and Moone,>
      text <And with their medicines make them to be congelate;>
      text <Which in the fire when they be examinate>
      text <May not abide, nor alter with complement:>
      text <For such Firmenting is not to our intent.>
    block
      text <But yet more kindly some other men doone,>
      text <Fermenting their medicines in this wise,>
      text <In Mercurie dissoluing both Sunne and Moone,>
      text <Till time with the spirit they will arise,>
      text <Subliming them together twice or thrice;>
      text <Then Fermentation therewith they make:>
      text <That is a way, but yet we it forsake.>
    block
      text <Some other there be which haue more hap,>
      text <To touch the troth in part of fermenting,>
      text <They amalgame their bodies with Mercurie like pap,>
      text <Then therevpon their medicines relenting:>
      text <These of our secrets haue some henting.>
      text <But not the truth with perfect complement,>
      text <Because they neither putrifie, nor alter their Ferment.>
    block
      text <That poynt therefore I will disclose vnto thee,>
      text <Looke how thou didst with thine vnperfect bodie,>
      text <Doe so with thy perfect bodies in each degree,>
      text <That is to say, first thou them putrifie,>
      text <Their former qualities destroying vtterly,>
      text <For this is wholly to our intent,>
      text <That first thou alter before thou ferment.>
    block
      text <To thy compound make firment the fourth part,>
      text <Which ferments been only of Sunne and Moone;>
      text <If thou therefore be maister of this Arte,>
      text <Thy Fermentation let thus be doone,>
      text <Fixe water and earth together soone,>
      text <And when thy medicine as waxe doth flowe,>
      text <Then vpon malgames looke thou it throwe.>
    block
      text <And when all that together is mixed,>
      text <Aboue the glasse well closed make thy fire,>
      text <And so continue it till all be fixed,>
      text <And well fermented to thy defire,>
      text <Then make Proiection after thy pleasure,>
      text <For that is medicine each deale perfite,>
      text <Thus must thou ferment both red and white.>
    block
      text <For like as flowre of wheate made into paste>
      text <Requireth ferment, which leauen we call>
      text <Of bread, that it may haue the kindly taste,>
      text <And become foode to man and woman cordiall:>
      text <Right so thy medicine ferment thou shall,>
      text <That it may taste of the Ferment pure,>
      text <At all assayes for euer to endure.>
    block
      text <And vnderstand that there be Ferments three,>
      text <Two be of bodies in nature cleene,>
      text <Which must be altred as I haue told thee;>
      text <The third most secret of which I meene,>
      text <Is the first earth of his water greene:>
      text <And therefore when the Lion doth thurst,>
      text <Make him to drinke till his belly burst.>
    block
      text <Of this a Question if I should mooue,>
      text <And aske of workers, what is this thing?>
      text <Anon thereby I should them prooue,>
      text <If they had knowledge of our fermenting:>
      text <For manie a man speaketh with wondring,>
      text <Of Robin hood and of his bowe,>
      text <Which neuer shot therein I trowe.>
    block
      text <For Fermentation true as I thee tell,>
      text <Is of the soule with the bodies incorporation,>
      text <Restoring to it the kindly smell,>
      text <With tast and colour by naturall conspissation,>
      text <Of things disseuered, a due reintegration,>
      text <Whereby the bodie of the spirit taketh impression,>
      text <That either the other may help to haue ingression.>
    block
      text <For like as bodies in their compaction corporall,>
      text <May not shewe out their qualities effectually,>
      text <Vntill the time that they become spirituall,>
      text <No more may spirits abide with bodies stedfastly,>
      text <Till they with them be confixate proportionally,>
      text <For then the bodie teacheth the spirit to suffer fire,>
      text <And the spirit the bodie to enter to thy defire.>
    block
      text <Therefore thy gold with gold thou must ferment,>
      text <With his owne water thy earth cleansed I meene,>
      text <Nought else to say but element with element,>
      text <The spirit of life onely going betweene,>
      text <For like as an adamant as thou hast seene>
      text <Draweth yron to him, so doth our earth by kinde,>
      text <Drawe downe to him his soule borne vp with winde.>
    block
      text <With winde therefore the soule lead out and in,>
      text <Mingle gold with gold, that is for to say,>
      text <Make Element with Element togetherrin>
      text <Till time all fire they suffer may,>
      text <For earth is Ferment withouten nay>
      text <To water, and water the earth vnto,>
      text <Our Fermentatio• in this wise must be doe.>
    block
      text <Earth is gold, and so is the soule also>
      text <Not common, but ours thus Elementate,>
      text <And yet thereto the Sunne must goe,>
      text <That by our wheele it may be alterate:>
      text <For so to ferment it must be preparate,>
      text <That it profoundly may ioyned bee,>
      text <With other natures as I said to thee.>
    block
      text <And whatsoeuer I haue here said of gold,>
      text <The same of siluer I will thou vnderstand,>
      text <That thou them putrifie and alter (as I haue told)>
      text <Ere thou thy medicine to firment take in hand:>
      text <Forsooth I could neuer finde him in England>
      text <Which in this wise to firment could me teach>
      text <Withouten error, by practise or by speach.>
    block
      text <Now of this chapter needeth to treate no more,>
      text <Sith I intend prolixitie to eschew;>
      text <Remember well my words therefore,>
      text <Which thou shalt proue by practise trew,>
      text <And Sunne and Moone looke thou renew,>
      text <That they may hold of the fift nature,>
      text <Then shall their tincture euermore endure.>
    block
      text <And yet a way there is most excellent,>
      text <Belonging vnto another working,>
      text <A water we make most redolent,>
      text <All bodies to oyle wherewith we bring,>
      text <With which our medicine we make flowing,>
      text <A quintessence this water we call,>
      text <In man which healeth diseases all.>
    block
      text <But with thy base, after my doctrine preperate>
      text <Which is our calx this must be done,>
      text <For when our bodies be so calcinate,>
      text <That water will to oyle dissolue them soone,>
      text <Make thou therefore oyle both of Sunne and Moone,>
      text <Which is ferment most fragrant for to smell.>
      text <And so the ninth gate is conquered of this Castell.>
    block
      text <The end of the ninth Gate.>

  text <Of Exaltation. The tenth Gate.>
    block
      text <PRoceede we now to the chapter of Exaltation,>
      text <Of which truly thou must haue knowledge pure,>
      text <But little it is different from Sublimation,>
      text <If thou conceiue it right I you ensure,>
      text <Hereto accordeth the holy scripture,>
      text <Christ saying thus, if I exalted be,>
      text <Then shall I draw all things vnto me.>
    block
      text <Our medicine if we exalt right so,>
      text <It shalbe thereby nobilitate,>
      text <That must be done in manners two,>
      text <From time the parties be dispousate,>
      text <Which must be crucified and examinate,>
      text <And then contumulate both man and wife,>
      text <And after reuiued by the spirit of life.>
    block
      text <Then vp to heauen they must exalted be,>
      text <There to be in bodie and soule glorificate,>
      text <For thou must bring them to such subtiltie,>
      text <that they ascend together to be intronizate,>
      text <In cloudes of clearenes to Angels consociate,>
      text <Then shall they draw as thou shalt see,>
      text <Al other bodies to their owne dignitee.>
    block
      text <If thou therefore the bodies wilt exalt,>
      text <First with the spirit of life thou them augment,>
      text <till time the earth be well subtilizate,>
      text <By naturall rectifying of euery Element,>
      text <Them vp exalting into the firmament,>
      text <Then much more precious shall they be than gold,>
      text <Because of the quintessence which they doe holde.>
    block
      text <For when the colde hath ouercome the heate,>
      text <Then into water the Ayre shall turned be,>
      text <And so two contraries together shall meete,>
      text <Till either with orher right well agree,>
      text <So into Ayre the water as I tell thee,>
      text <When heate of colde hath got domination,>
      text <Shall be conuerted by craft of our circulation.>
    block
      text <And of the Ayre then fire haue thou shall,>
      text <By loosing putrifying and subliming,>
      text <And fire thou hast of the earth materiall,>
      text <Thine Elements thus by craft disseuering,>
      text <Most especially thine earth well calcining,>
      text <And when they be each one made pure,>
      text <Then doe they holde all of the first nature.>
    block
      text <On this wise therefore make them be circulate,>
      text <Each into other exalting by and by,>
      text <And all in this one glasse surely sigillate,>
      text <Not with thine hands, but as I teach thee naturally,>
      text <Fire into water then turne first hardly,>
      text <For fire is in Ayre, which is in water existent,>
      text <And this conuersion accordeth to our intent.>
    block
      text <Then furthermore turne on thy wheele,>
      text <That into earth the ayre conuerted be,>
      text <Which will be done also right well,>
      text <For Ayre is in water being in earth trust me,>
      text <The water into fire contrarious in her qualitie,>
      text <Soone turne thou mayst for water in earth is,>
      text <Which is in fire, conuersion true is this.>
    block
      text <The wheele is now neere turned about,>
      text <Into ayre turne earrh which is the proper nest,>
      text <Of other Elements there is no doubt,>
      text <For earth in fire is, which in ayre taketh rest,>
      text <This circulation beginne thou in the west,>
      text <Then into the south, till they exalted bee,>
      text <Proceede duely, as in thy figure I haue taught thee.>
    block
      text <In which processe clearely thou mayst see,>
      text <Frō one extreame how to another thou mayst not go,>
      text <But by a meane, since they in qualities contrarious be,>
      text <And reason will forsooth that it be so,>
      text <As heate into colde, with other contraries •o,>
      text <Without their meanes as moyst to heate and colde,>
      text <Examples sufficient before this I haue tolde.>
    block
      text <Thus haue I taught thee how to make>
      text <Of all thine Elements a perfect circulation,>
      text <And at thy figure example to take,>
      text <How thou shalt make this foresaide Exaltation,>
      text <And of thy medicine in the Elements true graduation,>
      text <Till it be brought to a gueneritie temperate,>
      text <And then thou hast conquered the tenth gate.>
    block
      text <The end of the tenth Gate.>

  text <Of Multiplication. The eleuenth Gate.>
    block
      text <MVltiplication now to declare I proceede,>
      text <Which is by Philosophers in this wise defined>
      text <Augmentation it is of the Elixer indeede,>
      text <In goodnes and quantitie both for white and red,>
      text <Multiplication is therefore as they doe write,>
      text <That thing that doth augmēt medicines in each degree,>
      text <In colour, in odour, in vertue and also in quantitee.>
    block
      text <And why thou mayst this medicine multiplie,>
      text <Infinitely forsooth the cause is this,>
      text <For it is fire, which kindled will neuer die,>
      text <Dwelling with thee, as fire doth in houses,>
      text <Of which one sparke may make more fire ywis,>
      text <As muske in pigments and other spices mo,>
      text <In vertue multiplied, and our medicine right so.>
    block
      text <So he is rich which fire hath lesse or more,>
      text <Because he may so hugely it multiply,>
      text <And right so rich is he which any parte hath in store,>
      text <Of our Elixers which be augmentable infinitely,>
      text <One way if thou dissolue our pouders drye,>
      text <And make often times of them Congelation,>
      text <Thereof in goodnes then makest thou Augmentation.>
    block
      text <The second way both in goodnes and quantitie,>
      text <It multiplyeth by iterate Fermentation,>
      text <As in that chapter I shewed plainely to thee,>
      text <By diuers manners of naturall operation,>
      text <And also in the chapter of our Cibation,>
      text <Where thou mayst know how thou shalt multiplie,>
      text <Thy medicine with Mercurie infinitely.>
    block
      text <But and thou wilt both loose and eke ferment,>
      text <Both more in quantitie and better will it be:>
      text <And in such wise thou mayst it soone augment,>
      text <That in thy glasse it will growe like a tree,>
      text <The tree of Hermes named seemely to see,>
      text <Of which one pippin a thousand will multiplie,>
      text <If thou canst make thy proiection wittely.>
    block
      text <And like as Saffron when it is puluerizate,>
      text <By little and little if it with liquor be>
      text <Tempred, and then with much more liquor dilate,>
      text <Teyneth much more of liquor in quantitie,>
      text <Thā being whole in his grosse nature: so shalt thou see,>
      text <That our Elixer, the more it is made thinne,>
      text <The further in tincture it fastly will rinne.>
    block
      text <Keepe in thy fire therefore both euen and morrow,>
      text <From house to house that thou neede not to rinne,>
      text <Among thy neighbours thy fire to seeke or borrow,>
      text <The more thou keepest, the more good shalt thou win>
      text <Multiplying it alwaies more & more thy glasse within,>
      text <By feeding with Mercurie vnto thy liues end,>
      text <So shalt thou haue more than thou needest to spend.>
    block
      text <This matter is plaine I will no more>
      text <Write thereof, let reason thee guide,>
      text <Be neuer the bolder to sinne therefore,>
      text <But serue thy God the better in each tide:>
      text <And while that thou shalt in this life abide,>
      text <Beare this in minde, forget not I thee pray,>
      text <As thou shalt appeare before God at domes day.>
    block
      text <His owne great giftes therefore and his treasure,>
      text <Dispose thou vertuously, helping the poore at neede,>
      text <That in this world thou mayst to thee procure,>
      text <Mercy and grace with heauenly blisse to meede,>
      text <And pray to God deuoutly that he thee leade,>
      text <In at the twelfth gate, as he can best,>
      text <Soone after then thou shalt end thy conquest.>
    block
      text <The end of the eleuenth gate.>

  text <Of Proiection. The twelfth Gate.>
    block
      text <IN Proiection it shal be proued if our practise be pro∣fitable,>
      text <Of which it behoueth me the secrets here to moue,>
      text <Therefore if thy tincture be sure and not variable,>
      text <By a little of thy medicine thus mayst thou proue,>
      text <With mettle, or with Mercury as pitch it will cleaue,>
      text <And teyne in Proiection all fires to abide,>
      text <And soone it will enter and spread him full wide.>
    block
      text <But many by ignorance doe marre that they made,>
      text <When on mettals vnclensed Proiection they make,>
      text <For because of corruption their tinctures must fade,>
      text <Which they would not away first from the body take,>
      text <Which after Proiection be brittle blew and black,>
      text <That thy tincture therefore may euermore last,>
      text <First vpon ferment thy medicine see thou cast.>
    block
      text <Then brittle as glasse will thy ferment bee,>
      text <Vpon bodies clensed and made very pure,>
      text <Cast that brittle substance and soone shalt thou see,>
      text <That they shall be curiously coloured with tincture,>
      text <With all assayes for euer shall endure,>
      text <But profitable Proiection perfectly to make,>
      text <At the Psalmes of the Psalter example thou take.>
    block
      text <On Fundamenta cast first this psalme Nunc di••ittis,>
      text <Vpon verba mea, then cast Fundamenta beliue,>
      text <Then Verba vpon diligam, conceiue me with thy wits.>
      text <And diligam vpon attendite, if thou list to thriue,>
      text <Thus make thou Proiections, three, foure, or fiue,>
      text <Till the tincture of the medicine beginne to decrease,>
      text <And then it is time of Proiection to cease.>
    block
      text <By this mistie talking I meane nothing else,>
      text <But that thou must cast first the lesse on the more,>
      text <Encreasing aye the number as wisemen thee tells,>
      text <And keepe thou this secreat vnto thy selfe in store,>
      text <Be couetous of cunning it is no burden sore,>
      text <For he that ioyneth not the Elixer with bodies made cleane,>
      text <He wotteth not surely what Proiection doth meane>
    block
      text <Ten if thou multiplie first into ten,>
      text <One hundreth that number maketh sickerly,>
      text <If one hundreth into an hundreth be multiplied, then>
      text <Ten thousand is that number if thou count it wittely,>
      text <Then into as much more ten thousand to multiplie,>
      text <It is a thousand thousand; which multiplied ywis,>
      text <Into as much more a hundreth millions is.>
    block
      text <That hundreth millions being multiplyed likewise>
      text <Into ten thousand millions, as I to thee doe say,>
      text <Maketh so great a number I wot not what it is,>
      text <Thy number in Proiection thus multiplye alway:>
      text <Now childe of thy curtesie for me that thou pray,>
      text <Sith I haue tolde thee our secrets all and some,>
      text <To the which I beseech GOD by grace thou mayst come.>
    block
      text <Now hast thou conquered these gates twelue,>
      text <And all the Castle thou holdest at thy will,>
      text <Keepe thy secreats in store to thy selfe,>
      text <And the commaundements of God looke thou fulfill,>
      text <In fire see thou continue thy glasses still,>
      text <And multiply thy medicines aye more and more,>
      text <For wise men doe say, that store is no sore.>
    block
      text <Recapitulatio totius operis praedicti.>
      text <For to bring this Treatise to a finall ende,>
      text <And briefly here to conclude these secrets all,>
      text <Diligently looke thou, and to thy figure attend,>
      text <Which doth in it containe these secrets great & small,>
      text <And if thou it conceiue, both theoricall and practicall,>
      text <By figures and colours, by scripture plaine,>
    block
      text <It wittily conceiued, thou mayst not worke in vaine.>
    block
      text <Consider first the latitude of this precious Stone,>
      text <Beginning in the first side noted in the West,>
      text <Where the red man & the white woman be made one,>
      text <Spoused with the spirite of life to liue in rest,>
      text <Earth and water equally proportionate, that is best,>
      text <And one of the earth is good, and of the spirit three,>
